<br>
I have read of another interesting technique called <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Aggro Kiting</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  The idea is to choose an opponent that cannot outrun you or your pet, and get them good and pissed off at you, so they chase you and ignore the pet, and the pet clobbers them from behind.<br>
<br>
I am interested in more detailed advice about this technique.<br>
<br>
First of all, what is the best way to hold aggro?  In fact, this brings up another question whose answer I am unclear on, but does a single strike of a fast nuke generate more hate because it is fast, or is it simply the maximum damage of the nuke that determines the hate?  That is, do faster spells generate more hate only because they can be chain cast faster, or is there some innate hate bonus due to the speed of the spell?<br>
<br>
Seems like one way to build and hold hate might be to start the fight with an earth pet, do some nuking before the earth pet is killed, and then summon water for the backstabbing.  I should have a lot of hate built up, and it should chase me for a while.<br>
<br>
But then what?  With the ponee I can stay well ahead, so what I do I do?  Nuke every once in a while?  Wait for it to turn on the pet and then nuke?<br>
<br>
Seems like running in a circle might be best.<br>
<br>
And lastly, can I really solo anything that I could not by simply chaining pets?  Certainly if a creature chews up pets too fast then aggro kiting might work, but then there seems little margin for error.  Compared to chaining, the pet is doing more melee damage, the mob is taking at least some more nukes, but damage shields don't count.  I am also running instead of medding, as I would be if I were chaining.<br>
<br>
Seems like with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Velocity</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> I would like to keep a single pet for the whole kite, with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Burnout 4</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  But do I wind up aggro kiting with multiple pets?<br>
<br>
I am interested in your observations, ideas, and opinions regarding this apparently little used technique.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Master ArchMage Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uzacatac.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zacatac</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 1044<br> <font color=#333333>(8/6/02 5:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=624.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Aggro Kiting with Pets?</span><hr size=1> Well I have only done this with a druid partner actually.  But the idea still works with just yourself.<br>
<br>
1.  Use water pet, give it velocity or expedience, turn OFF taunt (very important) and normal buff.  Don't bother with DS unless you have clicky robe.<br>
<br>
2.  Don't use rain spells.  DD only, the biggest one you have.  It will cause a ton of aggro, stay close to mob but out of its reach and it will follow you.<br>
<br>
3.  Mob will chase you around, pet will continue to beat on it.  Make sure you are in an area where you won't get adds and just run around back and forth.  <br>
<br>
4.  When mob stops to hit pet, Nuke it again so it runs after you.  Eventually mob will wear down and pet can finish it off.<br>
<br>
When I did this with a druid partner, druid would snare and we would get about 100 yards apart and ping-pong the mob back and forth (/cheer Bolt spell) while pet beat on it and we took turns taking aggro.<br>
